node.text: Created by 3D artist @ChadKnight, these jaw-dropping sculptures hijacks the viewer’s third eye and mind with intensity and curiosity. The sculptures usually start off as images in his mind, often inspired by something he has seen or gone through. He imagines them, starts doodling, uses his computer and then gets into a zone and starts creating. One of the reason making these sculptures so special is they blend so well with the environment and make you think they are actually built on top of that instead of just digital art. #architectanddesign

node.text:
Project of the Week: Casa Criollo is a house for rent located in #Oaxaca, #Mexico. The house, completed in 2019, was designed in collaboration with architect Javier Sanchez of the @JSaArquitectura. 
Casa Criollo is an invitation to relax and escape.
Just behind the restaurant nestled in an elegant bohemian house listed as a UNESCO heritage, the house that can comfortably accommodate 4 guests, consists of a living room with large windows, two double bedrooms, and two bathrooms with walk-in rainfall shower. 

The interiors, created in collaboration with the Mexican interior design firm @Habitacion116, feature a minimalist and contemporary style.
The decoration is natural and raw, with concrete floors and walls, neutral and sober tones, touches of salmon spread throughout the home, wooden furniture, and typical textiles. All combined with objects and accessories highlighting local know-how and craftsmanship. 

The space is comfortable, with great attention to the details. Outside there is a beautiful terrace, 
a comfortable sitting area, a wooden dining table, 
a swimming pool with sun loungers for cooling off and enjoy the sun, a built-in sauna, and a hammock for relaxing. The combination of native plants and concrete creates a spacious and calm atmosphere. 📸: @rafaelgamo, @allthewildair #architectanddesign

node.text: With a colorful and ancient history, Mont-Saint-Michel has over one thousand years of stories under its belt. It's distinctively located on a rocky tidal island, which means that it's only an island during high tide and you can walk across its sands during low tide. Besides learning about its history, visitors can also enjoy beautiful architecture, exquisite food, and great shopping. 📸: @_pifou, @mindz.eye #architectanddesign

node.text:
Naqshe Jahan Square in #Isfahan has been registered as a World Heritage Site by UNESCO. This historical square embraces some iconic monuments, one of them is Imam Mosque, it’s better to say the one of the most significant ones. This mosque is known also as Shah Mosque.
Imam Mosque is the best example of a thousand-year tradition in building mosques. The mosque is comprised of a main dome, two Shabestans (prayers hall), four porches, four minarets, and also including two seminaries next to the mosque to study theology.

The mosque was built near 400 years ago by the command of Shah Abbas I Safavi, Abbas the Great. The architecture and decorations of the mosque are really picturesque. One of the wonders of its architecture is the angle between the entrance and the main axis of the structure. The Propylaea is toward square to maintain the symmetry and harmony with the other buildings of square, while the structure of mosque is rotated toward Qibla. The wise and talented architect dissolved this rotation by combining some empty space in arch forms, and when you enter the mosque you don’t recognize a rotating plan.

Decorations of the Propylaea are really impressive, especially the magnificent tiles. When you want to enter the mosque, it’s better to take look above to shock. There is a perfect Muqarnas technique which has been decorated by the shrubs. Mihrab is the other significant part of the mosque. 📸: @fatemeghaderi #architectanddesign

node.text:
@Paul_Milinski‘s 3D universes function as havens for the mind. Every detail is thought out with the greatest care, and contributes to the idyllic atmosphere of these dream spaces.

He designs places where architecture and nature meet. Paul describes this hyperrealistic ballet, where every element has its own place as “Where leaking light through leaves becomes nature’s disco ball. Places where all living things are seen as equal and where human elements conform to the environment.” #architectanddesign

node.text:
Did you know that, the city of #Venice is not one island. It’s actually 118 small islands, all linked together by bridges.
The island of Lido in the south is famous for its long sandy beach, and many of the islands have a different feel. Photo & edit: @lennart #architectanddesign
